Some targets were not met as lab was recruited in Q3 - Accelerator Lab Team on board - Head of Solutions Mapping, Exploration and Experimentation were recruited and participated in an Accelerator Lab Network Bootcamp in Kigali in August 2019. The full team was operational at the Zimbabwe country office by October 2019.
1.3 - solution tested at micro-level • The Accelerator Lab is engaging in the first phase of experiment cycle one which focuses on: Navigating Informality and Formality. This issue was a claim that was identified during the sensemaking session held in July 2019 through the convening of Zimbabwean ministries by the Office of the President and Cabinet. A stakeholder mapping exercise was done in October 2019 to identify the key people who can contribute to the process of issues mapping. The identified cities for engagement were: Harare, Bulawayo, Mutare and Gweru. -Methodology: Issue Mapping • The facilitator engaged participants in conversation on the informal economy and sector. The participants interactively stated the issues that are found within the informal sector and these will be categorized under but not limited to the following subject areas: Technological, Political, Financial, Socio-cultural, Educational, Infrastructure and Legislative. The highest ranking subject area is the one that the experiment will focus on. - Solution Mapping • A mixed and participatory approach was used in solution mapping. This included: • Observation of local communities within the informal sector and understanding how they solve their challenges • Face to Face Interviews which will be guided by structured questions on capture cards to get detailed information, attitudes, behaviours and experiences on the issues identified under the informal sector • A collection of human narrative stories on vendors will be conducted to form a synopsis for the ethnographic project following the life of vendors in 2020 • An assessment of potential solutions observed will be done and these solutions will be juxtaposed with similar ones found online The result was the identification of a solution through the Bulawayo Issue mapping session that will be tested out in Harare. This will begin in January 20202.2 2.1 - Accelerator Lab Zimbabwe produced 2 blogs in 2019 target was not met as lab was recruited Q3, the blog titles are; - The informal journey to experimentation - African Cities - Disrupting the Urban Future 2.2 - At least 1 Protocol tested by national counterpart • A sensemaking workshop was held in July 2019 with different government ministries and relevant government departments, convened by the Office of the President and Cabinet of Zimbabwe and UNDP. The sensemaking workshop brought together 40 civil servants from the newly established policy clusters, to create a shared and collaborative understanding of five key transformational programmes from the Transitional Stabilisation Programme (TSP): Infrastructure, Devolution, Social Safety Nets, Currency Reform, Peace Building and Reconciliation. The purpose of the sensemaking workshop was to create a shared understanding of entry points for acceleration, that cut across key government programmes and identify actions which may lead to transformative impacts. The Sensemaking Workshop produced seven claims, which were reorganized into three key claims. These three forces create system dynamics that are felt across board;
Claim 01: Navigating Between Formality and Informality Claim 02: Amplifying Voice Claim 03: Exponentially Vulnerable 2.3 - Ministry of Local Government, Office of the President learned about the Accelerator lab methods through the sensemaking workshop was held in July 2019. 3.2 Accelerator Global publications, global calls and onboarding sessions for new accelerator lab members 3.3 Target met 3.4 Target met
